no-tiny-wrapper-function

Warns on functions and methods that only forward directly to another call.

Source: custom rule for lintcn
Severity: warn (does not block CI)

The goal is to stop agents from creating tiny wrapper abstractions when they
should inline the call directly at the usage site instead.

The Problem

These helpers often do not add meaningful behavior. They just rename a call and
make the codebase more indirect:

  export function createTestStore(): ConversationStore {
    return new ConversationStore(createMemoryRedis())
  }

  const save = (file: string) => write(file)

  class Repo {
    persist(value: string) {
      return write(value)
    }
  }

What Gets Flagged

- Functions whose whole body is a direct `return call(...)`
- Methods whose whole body is a direct `return call(...)`
- Expression-bodied arrows like `const save = (file) => write(file)`
- Direct constructor forwarding like `return new Repo(value)`

This includes wrappers such as:

  function persist(value: string) {
    return write(value)
  }

  class Repo {
    persist(value: string) {
      return write(value)
    }
  }

What Is Allowed

Short functions and methods are allowed when they add behavior, even if the
body still fits in a single call expression. Computed arguments count as real
behavior, so wrappers like these stay allowed:

  function persist(value: string) {
    return write(normalize(value))
  }

  function persist(user: { name: string }) {
    return write(user.name)
  }

  export function createTestStore(): ConversationStore {
    return new ConversationStore(createMemoryRedis())
  }

These non-call helpers are also allowed:

  function sum(a: number, b: number) {
    return a + b
  }

  const getName = (user: { name: string }) => user.name

  class Counter {
    next() {
      return this.value + 1
    }
  }

Example Warning Messages

Function example:

  This function only forwards directly to another call. Inline the call instead
  of creating a wrapper function.

Method example:

  This method only forwards directly to another call. Inline the call instead
  of creating a wrapper function.
